\cf0 	This design however did not seem incredibly practical in transportation and also did not solve the issue of reducing friction when pulling on the hose. Our team decided to rethink our original idea and attempt to create something similar with products that did exist or that we could create.\
	We first attempted to solve the issue of attaching the system to a corner or wall. We soon realized that it would be very difficult to create something that could attach to any surface or scenario, so we decided to make a couple that could all attach to our system. The first issue to tackle was a door frame. In general, these would be a similar size, but could be made of different types of material. So attach to this, we envision something similar to a bear trap. We pictured a spring loaded clamp that had rubber teach on its prongs that would be able to create a lot of friction on many different surfaces. The reason clamps on the market would not work for a corner is that they do not create enough inward force to create friction. A very powerful spring loaded clamp would be able to overcome this problem.\
	Our next issue was a corner. We realized through testing that clamps could not stay attached to a corner, and that suction cups only work for a limited amount of surfaces. So we finally determined that attachment to a corner was not feasible. Instead, we decided a telescoping stand placed at the base of the corner would work better. This would need to have suction cups or a rubber coating on its \'91feet; in order to create enough friction to not be pulled along the floor, and would also have to be very wide and short to reduce torque. Also, shortening the back leg (if the stand were a tripod) and keeping the front two legs taller would help to direct more force into the floor, further helping to increase friction. Something similar to a camera tripod with a center support would work well for this purpose.\
