\cf0 	When brainstorming how to work on a stair, we figured that the stand used for the corner could also be used when going up stairs. Its telescoping abilities would allow it to have different legs at different heights. This would increase its flexibility in use and would help fire fighters in ease of placement.\
	The most crucial part of the system, however, was what would hold the hose and help to alleviate friction. What we decided on a a diamond-shaped frame that would hold rollers, comprised of aluminum rods and bearings. The hose would sit between two rollers and would therefore be able to move smoothly across the system with a pull by a fire fighter. It would also have a clasp on one side that would allow it to be opened at one corner, the hose placed inside, and then have the system shut around the hose, alleviating a need for the hose fitting to fit through. This system would also be hinged on two axes so it would have 180 degrees of motion in both the x and y planes. This would then allow the frame to be positioned at any position in a hemisphere and allow the frame to pivot in the direction of any force being applied to it. The base of the frame would then have a screw on it allowing it to be attached to any of the bases.\
